title: For Sale:  Saiga 12
postcontent: Saiga 12 Seimi-automatic Shotgun, original box, five (5) factory original (Russian) magazines, two (2) 2-round magazine plugs, Russian Collimator sight with carrying case & box, Russian skeleton stock, & Tri-rail forearm. You already know what a Saiga-12 is, so I won't bore you with info on the weapon. This one's been fired 20 times, the scope was zeroed using 2-3/4" Winchester slugs at 50 yards & it will "cloverleaf" all 3 at that distance. I put this shotgun together to hunt dear here in Ohio, but never got to take into the woods. The magazine plugs can be installed in the standard capacity mags so the weapon can be legally hunted with. For those of you unfamiliar with the Russian Collimator sights, they are the best, non-magnified electronic "dot" scope made for the Kalashnikov series of weapons & they work fantastic on Saiga shotguns. These sights are TOUGH & are quickly mounted & removed from the weapon via its side rail. If you own a Kalashnikov, you already know this is the best way to scope one. The sight has multiple reticles (dot, pyramid, NATO dot w/pyramid, & cross) that can be cycled through by pressing a button on the side of the sight. The reticles are also adjustable for brightness. And this is all done while running on plain ol' AA batteries. I have one of these scopes on each of my AKs. The buttstock  has a raised cheek piece for use with the scope. When you remove the scope to use the vent rib & bead sight, you can shift the cheek piece over & out of the way. The only part of this weapon that is not original Russian is the tri-railed forearm. I believe it was made here in the states. Well, that's it. I never had anything mechanically modified because, well, it's a Kalashnikov, works! I put 20 slugs through it, cleaned it, & placed it in my safe. Now I need room for more toys, so it has to go. The first $900.00 gets it all. Thanks.

title: For Sale:  Buyer Beware - Rick Pickering rspickering@gulftel.com
postcontent:
I bought a rifle from Rick Pickering from Alabama.  He sent pictures, and I inquired further on any and all blemishes on the gun.  He informed me the wood was excellent, and there was only 1 spot of bluing rubbed under the lever.  When I picked up the rifle from my FFL it had a large scratch on the barrel which was easily felt with a fingernail, and 2 spots on the barrel where the bluing was nearly worn thru.  He never mentioned those issues in our initial negotiations.
Before I ever picked up the rifle, however, my FFL called me and said it was the worst packing he had ever seen.  Alarmed, I contacted Rick, who informed me if there was a problem, he'd take the rifle back and refund my money. Awesome!
Not awesome, because when I picked it up, and saw the scratch, and 2 spots of worn bluing, I contacted him and asked if he would take it back, or send me $40 towards me getting it reblued.  He refused both, and any attempts to make it right.  He is now accusing me of extorting him, and claims I'm crazy to expect a 40 year old rifle to not have some issues.  He also claims he owned the rifle for 20 years, but never knew of the scratch, or the 2 worn blued spots.  He doesnt understand my major gripe is that he omitted informing me of those issues, when in good faith he should have, and if he didnt know about them (highly unlikely), he should have done the right thing and taken the rifle back with a full refund upon receipt.
Buyer beware, do not deal with Rick Pickering.  Feel free to email me if you have other questions about Rick Pickering.
Bamaboy473
Smith & Wesson
ammo
Marlin rifle

title: For Sale:  Here is STEYR HAHN - M1912 9mm NAZI, POLICE Eagle/L.  Matching, Non-Import w/ Holster....
postcontent: Got Steyr Hahn Model 1912 pistol that was originally manufactured in Austria in 1919. The HV-Eagle-30 proof on the right side of the trigger guard indicates the pistol was issued to Austrian police forces in 1930. During the Nazi era, in about 1940-1941, it was reworked for issue to the German Police forces. As part of the rework, the pistol received a new barrel chambered for 9mm Parabellum. To indicate the change, the slide was stamped with "08", the German designation for the 9mm service cartridge. The pistol was also marked with the Eagle/N test proof on the barrel and left side of the frame as well as the Eagle/L Police acceptance on the right. The frame, slide and barrel all have matching serial numbers and the Steyr "K" proof is present on all parts. There are NO import markings as this is likely a WWII "bring-back" pistol. The arsenal finish rates about 92-93% overall with some thinning to the grip straps and sharp edges. There is no significant rust or pitting. The original checkered walnut grips are in excellent condition, free of cracks or chips. The mechanics are in good working order and the bore is excellent with bright, sharp rifling. It comes with an original/correct pebble-grain brown leather holster that is in very good condition. Two stripper clips are included as well...

Both sterling inlays are marked with the initials SS indicating silver of 92.5 percent purity. The tang mark reads ULSTER / LIMITED EDITION and on the reverse side is stamped U.S.A. 

The knife is presented in an 8" x 11" simulated leather case with a removable wood frame encasing the knife behind a clear protective shield, which can be slid off. The wood frame can be displayed on a desk, or hung on the wall. The lettering on the simulated leather case is printed in silver, matching the silver knife. 

No coin was issued with the silver edition, instead there is a raised scout trefoil embossed on the cases velvet interior. This knife has been kept in my personal collection.

Information note: This limited production knife issue was manufactured by Imperial Schrade under the Ulster trademark. 

There were three issues of the knife ::::: Brass 11,400 produced - Silver 500 produced - Gold 100 produced.
